segments.text: Forrest Rangers!
Today, we present the final program in this second series on forest conservation, featuring Bill Scott, Forest Ranger.
Our scene is Beaver Dam Forest.
It is a late summer day, and the sun is about to set in golden glory.
Outwardly, the forest and all of its living plants and creatures seem at peace with the world.
And yet, on the narrow woods road that runs along Storm Creek,
Small pebbles and bits of soil have been rolling down from above all day, a danger signal of more serious things to come.
But Ranger Bill's niece, June, his two young assistants, Joe and Sam, have no knowledge of what's taking place above Storm Creek as they travel along the forest highway in the pickup truck.
Even though this is the last day the three will spend on Beaver Dam Forest this summer, they seem unusually gay in spirit, excited, and downright frisky.
Boy, won't Ranger Bill be surprised?
I just want to see his face, that's all.
A surprise, Potty.
Uncle Bill will be pleased.

He's always doing something for other people.
It's about time someone did something for him.

Jesus.

You bet, June.
Just look at the stuff back there in the truck.

Wood for a thousand uses.
And water.
To drink, for irrigation, and to provide electrical power.
Yes.
And food for livestock.
And food and shelter for wildlife.
Don't forget recreation.
Outdoor fun and relaxation.
But it takes planning, June, and good care to keep the soil fertile and the land producing.
You sound like a forestry encyclopedia comes alive.
Well, it's not as funny as it may sound, Joe.
We need our forests so very much, but we've just got to take care of them, keep them green and growing.

Participating in this series on forest conservation have been the following members of the radio workshop of the New York City Board of Education.
Larry Corn was Joe, Sam was played by Bob Dash, Joan Jackson was cast in the role of June.
